## COMMUNICATION PROTOCOLS

### WITH KATHY

**Frequency:** Minimum 2-3 times per week, more if she requests
**Method:** Phone calls (she has new phone from Amy)
**Tone:** Calm, reassuring, detailed but not overwhelming
**Key Principles:**
- Always acknowledge her feelings and concerns
- Provide specific information, not vague reassurances
- Give timelines and next steps
- Remind her of progress made
- Emphasize her safety and security
- Avoid information overload
- End calls on positive note

**Topics to Cover:**
- Financial status updates
- Banking progress (Austin Bank activation)
- Bill payment confirmations
- Discharge planning progress
- Legal matters (carefully, don't create anxiety)
- Home preparation status

**Topics to Avoid:**
- Complex legal details
- Negative interactions with prior counsel
- Frustrations with bureaucratic processes
- Anything that increases anxiety without purpose

### WITH AMY

**Frequency:** Daily brief updates, weekly detailed check-ins
**Method:** Email for non-urgent, text for urgent, calls for complex
**Tone:** Collaborative, appreciative, clear instructions
**Key Principles:**
- Provide clear, actionable tasks
- Explain the "why" behind requests
- Offer multiple payment options (Venmo, call Eric for card)
- Acknowledge her efforts and thank her regularly
- Pay promptly and fairly
- Don't overload with tasks
- Respect her boundaries and capacity

**Payment Schedule:**
- Weekly Venmo for hours worked
- Immediate Venmo for expenses (upon request)
- Bonus for exceptional work or extra hours
- Clear documentation of all payments

**Task Delegation:**
- Only delegate tasks Amy can reasonably complete
- Provide resources and support
- Don't expect Amy to handle complex financial/legal matters
- Respect her role as care coordinator, not financial manager

### WITH GILMER CONNECTED CARE

**Primary Contact:** Steven Grantham, LBSW (social worker)
**Frequency:** As needed, weekly minimum during discharge planning
**Method:** Email for documentation, calls for urgent
**Tone:** Professional, collaborative, appreciative
**Key Principles:**
- Acknowledge their excellent care of Kathy
- Ask questions clearly and specifically
- Request written documentation
- Follow up on commitments
- Coordinate through proper channels
- Respect their processes and timelines

### WITH SERVICE PROVIDERS (Banks, Utilities, Vendors)

**Method:** Email preferred for documentation, calls for urgent
**Tone:** Professional, firm but polite, persistent
**Key Principles:**
- Always reference POA authority
- Provide documentation proactively
- Follow up in writing
- Keep records of all communications
- Escalate when necessary but professionally
- Document names, dates, reference numbers

